TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Multiple Attribute Utility Theory Approach to Ranking and Selection
AU  - Butler, John
AU  - Morrice, Douglas J.
AU  - Mullarkey, Peter W.
Y1  - 2001/06/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.47.6.800.9812
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.47.6.800.9812
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 800
EP  - 816
VL  - 47
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Managers of large industrial projects often measure performance by multiple attributes. For example, our paper is motivated by the simulation of a large industrial project called a land seismic survey, in which project performance is based on duration, cost, and resource utilization. To address these types of problems, we develop a ranking and selection procedure for making comparisons of systems (e.g., project configurations) that have multiple performance measures. The procedure combines multiple attribute utility theory with statistical ranking and selection to select the best configuration from a set of possible configurations using the indifference-zone approach. We apply our procedure to results generated by the simulator for a land seismic survey that has six performance measures, and describe a particular type of sensitivity analysis that can be used as a robustness check.
AB  - Managers of large industrial projects often measure performance by multiple attributes. For example, our paper is motivated by the simulation of a large industrial project called a land seismic survey, in which project performance is based on duration, cost, and resource utilization. To address these types of problems, we develop a ranking and selection procedure for making comparisons of systems (e.g., project configurations) that have multiple performance measures. The procedure combines multiple attribute utility theory with statistical ranking and selection to select the best configuration from a set of possible configurations using the indifference-zone approach. We apply our procedure to results generated by the simulator for a land seismic survey that has six performance measures, and describe a particular type of sensitivity analysis that can be used as a robustness check.
